It=E2=80=99s Friday, March 27. This is The Front Page, your daily window in=
to the world of The Free Press=E2=80=94and our take on the world at large. =
If you missed TGIF, catch it here [ https://substack.com/redirect/366cd8f3-=
e98d-4fc6-a9b4-588562d58235?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0Ib_nbCOLc=
-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ]. (Nellie is in rare form.) Today: Tony Blair on the =
West=E2=80=99s antisemitism blind spot. Matti Friedman on the Jewish volunt=
eers who parachuted back into Nazi-occupied Europe. Jean Twenge wonders: Wh=
ere did all the bisexual women go? Gabe Kaminsky speaks to the CEO whose Tr=
ump pardon didn=E2=80=99t cost him a cent. And much more.
But first: when Ozempic is bad for the soul.
There are scientific miracles=E2=80=94and then there=E2=80=99s Ozempic. It =
curbs appetites, of course, which can lead to significant weight loss, and =
eliminate obesity for many people. It=E2=80=99s also been found to reduce a=
lcohol consumption and to cause people to cut down=E2=80=94or cut out=E2=80=
=94smoking. Not to mention that it may be helpful for treating drug addicti=
on and even compulsive shopping.
But we=E2=80=99re also starting to understand that, for some Ozempic users,=
 it has some not-so-pleasant side effects. As Evan Gardner reports in today=
=E2=80=99s lead story, one such possible side effect is an overwhelming let=
hargy, even depression. One Ozempic user told Evan that the emotional impac=
t of the drug was almost unbearable. =E2=80=9CI just feel worthless,=E2=80=
=9D she told him. Others have lost their sex drive, their desire to be arou=
nd other people, or the motivation they always had at work. Patients who su=
ffer these effects face a difficult choice: to stay on a drug that allows t=
hem to gain control over their appetite and their weight, or get off it bec=
ause of the way it affects their mental health. Evan talks to the Ozempic u=
sers who have lost their hunger=E2=80=94for everything.
MORE FROM THE FREE PRESS
EDITORS=E2=80=99 PICKS
It=E2=80=99s been a busy week in our newsroom. If you=E2=80=99re still catc=
hing up, start with one of these not-to-be-missed Free Press investigations=
=2E
First, Olivia Reingold=E2=80=99s probe of Chicago=E2=80=99s perplexing =E2=
=80=9CPeacekeepers=E2=80=9D program, part of a billion-dollar crime-fightin=
g experiment, which pays ex-gang members a weekly stipend to keep their nei=
ghbors out of trouble. Today, a growing chorus of city leaders, law enforce=
ment officials, and even one donor are saying it doesn=E2=80=99t work. Read=
 Olivia=E2=80=99s investigation into the program, and watch her video repor=
t here [ https://substack.com/redirect/222fbbd3-a34b-4487-8ae9-eba4189409e5=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMWp1ZGpwIn0.5o04gUnkd-Msu0Ib_nbCOLc-sw15-DjXlvGx8bWpSeo ].
Next up, the latest in Tanya Lukyanova=E2=80=99s Epstein files investigatio=
n. Earlier this month, Tanya spoke with Liza Grinenko, who was nearly recru=
ited into Epstein=E2=80=99s web by his assistant Svetlana =E2=80=9CLana=E2=
=80=9D Pozhidaeva. Soon after, Pozhidaeva received a sympathetic profile in=
 The Wall Street Journal=E2=80=94which caused Tanya to dig deeper into Pozh=
idaeva=E2=80=99s story. Was she a victim=E2=80=94or an enabler? After Pozhi=
daeva DMed Tanya and said she wanted to talk, things got interesting.
Finally, don=E2=80=99t miss Jay Solomon=E2=80=99s investigation into the cu=
rious case of 21-year-old Calla Walsh, the progressive activist who once ca=
mpaigned for Senators Ed Markey and Elizabeth Warren. Her life today looks =
a little different: Walsh is now living in a Hezbollah-controlled neighborh=
ood of Beirut, making pro-Iran propaganda=E2=80=94and she=E2=80=99s on a U.=
S. government watch list. This is a tale of our times.
The ongoing war in Iran continued to grab headlines this week, but there wa=
s one part of the narrative conspicuously missing: What is Iran=E2=80=99s r=
eal reason for waging war? Yardena Schwartz argues that for the Islamic Rep=
ublic, this is a holy war=E2=80=94one aimed at preserving Islam as a coloni=
zing force, overthrowing Israel, and bringing the entire Middle East under =
Islamic rule.
If you want a break from the war news this weekend, we get it. But before y=
ou start your digital detox, read Niall Ferguson=E2=80=99s latest essay on =
why Iran=E2=80=99s choking of the global energy supply is worth your attent=
ion. Niall warns us: History shows that oil shocks like the one we=E2=80=99=
re currently experiencing almost always bring about a major financial downt=
urn.
Meanwhile, our Coleman Hughes debated one of the most hard-line critics of =
Israel in the public sphere: independent journalist Glenn Greenwald. Watch =
their debate here [ https://substack.com/redirect/7c262a67-27a7-4b37-bbb3-9=
